    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-09-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-09-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <head>245. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d245fn0"
                        >Source: Department of State, Conference Files: Lot 64 D 560, CF 1490.
                        Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName> and cleared
                        by <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss> and the White House on October 14. The
                        meeting was held at the White House. See also <ref target="#d242">Documents
                            242</ref>–<ref target="#d244">244</ref> and <ref target="#d246"
                            >246</ref>–<ref target="#d247">247</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">PSV/<gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>/4</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1959-09-30">September 30, 1959</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">SEGNI VISIT</p>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Common Market</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows the same list of participants as <ref target="#d242">Document
                        242</ref>.]</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SA1">Segni</persName> then turned to the question of
                    the Common Market, referring to the talks with the President in Paris with
                    respect to increasing political consultation among the Six.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d245fn1">At the <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Ministerial
                        Meeting December 16–18, 1958.</note> He wanted to reaffirm that such
                    political consultation was not directed against anyone and did not diminish in
                    any way the importance which the Italians ascribe to <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >NATO</gloss>. The President replied that he had not had any suspicions as
                    to the Italian attitude in this respect.</p>
                <p>The President then noted that it was time for the luncheon to begin and suggested
                    that the talks be resumed after the luncheon. The meeting broke up at 1:00
                    p.m.</p>
            </div>
